Track T800-CDi review
Andrew English rides a diesel-powered motorcycle, the Track T800-CDi. 4
The diesel Track T800's Smart engine ensures the machine is no slouch
Photo: ANDREW CROWLEY	By Andrew English
6:30AM GMT 19 Feb 2012
Comments
My grandfather taught motorcycle dispatch riders in the Artists Rifles during the Second World War and I could feel his spirit as I climbed on the Track T800. It’s a cold day, so wait for the glow plugs, then thumb the starter – “dakka, dakka”, the engine turns over slowly and catches. “Diesel!” I could almost hear my grandfather explode. “What sort of motorcycle is that?”
You wouldn’t know it from the exhaust pipe, which remains impressively smoke free, but the vibration from this three-cylinder turbodiesel (out of Mercedes-Benz’s Smart car), shakes the handmade trail bike’s windscreen in a dozen different directions. Not that you feel it on the foot pegs or the bars. Only your ears get assaulted on this Dutch-built machine – it sounds like a coffee grinder. With a belt-driven, continuously variable transmission and a centrifugal clutch, you simply turn the throttle and pull away, although with a seat height of 2ft 11in, the sheer loftiness of the T800 leaves shorter riders scrabbling. Be bold with the throttle and getaways are remarkably smooth, but with a dry weight of almost 500lb, you need to balance the centrifugal clutch against the back brake for stability in low-speed manoeuvres. Jez Hermer, the ex-Royal Marine boss of Ovik, which imports the T800, confesses that he struggles to touch the ground and has managed to drop the machine while testing. “We are working on a lower seat,” he says with a grin. Related Articles
