Diesel motorcycles are not new, of course. Remember the cement-mixer-engined Royal Enfield Taurus, capable of 200mpg, but with performance measured on a calendar and retina-detaching vibration? The Hayes Diversified Technologies M1030M1 diesel is no longer in production, but this Kawasaki-based machine showed enough promise to tempt the US Marine Corps. And it is the prize of potential military sales that causes so many to tilt at the diesel-bike windmill. Nato forces have operated a single-fuel policy (diesel) since the mid-Eighties, but nobody has yet come up with a truly successful diesel motorbike. The quest has become something of a cottage industry; there’s even a highly regarded Triumph Tiger conversion using the same Smart 800cc turbodiesel, by Belfast engineer Neil Laughlin. The Track is the brainchild of talented engineer Erik Vegt, of EVA Products in Holland. He and his small team have painstakingly engineered the machine using the last word in components, including a chrome-molybdenum-alloy-steel tubular frame, specially built to accommodate the Smart diesel and its bespoke transmission. “We say this is a half-million-mile driveline, which gives problems for the rest of the machine; the components have to be top quality as well,” says Hermer. And they are: WP spring/dampers, Brembo brakes, Excel wheels and a BMW-inspired shaft drive should last the course and can be individually serviced. Hermer is currently developing a new Kevlar drivebelt that should be good for 18,000 miles and that would be the limiting factor for the service intervals. The T800-CDi is not fast in the current idiom of super trail bikes, but twist the throttle and it moves along deceptively quickly, although you are in no danger of lifting the front wheel, which many might regard as a safety factor. “I’d also like to see anti-lock brakes as standard,” says Hermer. Above 80mph the aerodynamics start to take a toll on performance, but you can make rapid progress on the T800. Top speed is quoted at 102mph, with fuel consumption above 80mpg which, with a 4.2-gallon tank, gives a range exceeding 340 miles. The weight discourages rapid changes in direction and means you have to tug the machine down into a series of bends, but it corners well, with supple damping that allows you to accurately place it in corners. Hermer thinks the damping needs tweaking and it is certainly soft on the initial inch of travel, but after that it feels quite firm and I wouldn’t want much more rebound dialled in. The comfort is exemplary and you could ride this bike all day, helped by the effective MRA windscreen, hand shields and heated grips. And when you want to stop, the brakes are beautifully weighted and powerful. Issues? While the all-up weight is well short of that of a Honda Pan-European touring bike, the seat height makes it tricky at very low speeds and I also found the back brake pedal slightly obscured by the transmission casing. In spite of his vast experience developing specialised military vehicles, Hermer knows that military sales are going to be difficult. “I think UK forces have largely given up on motorcycles,” he says. “The last of the old MT350 Harley-Davidsons and Pan-Europeans have been sold off.”
The forces also seem to have lost the nerve that was so implicit in the image of the lone dispatch rider getting through against all the odds. The late Alan Coren once wrote in Punch about how, when the balloon went up, he would like to be astride a BSA, in a long dispatch rider’s coat, with a hip flask full of cherry brandy and a slab of Bendicks Sporting and Military chocolate. Yet two years ago, the RAF was all aflutter about suffering more injuries to personnel riding motorbikes in their leisure than it was in Iraq. So Hermer is trying to interest the emergency services, the AA and RAC, the blood transfusion and organ transfer services. “We’re in a difficult period of development,” he admits. “The price needs to come down.”
You need to do a lot of miles to make a machine like this pay, but that’s exactly what it has been built to do. On beautiful West Country roads, I probably looked more like the dispatch rider from the Monty Python sketch delivering the funniest joke in the world than one of my grandfather’s intrepid pupils, but the T800 looked the part and seems to have more than enough vim. THE FACTS Track T800-CDi Price/on sale: £15,995/now Power/torque: 50bhp @ 3,000rpm/74bhp @ 1,800rpm Top speed: 102mph Fuel tank/range: 4.2 gallons/320 miles Verdict: The best-ever oil-burning bike, but it’s still too expensive Telegraph rating: Four out of five stars For more information visit the Ovik Special Vehicles website. Motorbikes
